In <35ggvh$2eb@news.cerf.net> aetc@nic.cerf.net (Tony Burzio) writes:

>In article <1994Sep17.183718.2857@belvedere.sbay.org> root@belvedere.sbay.org (David E. Fox) writes:
>>
>>Linux loads at the 1 megabyte boundary and remaps the 0-640K area, from
>>what I know. This isn't a problem.
>
>Does Linux do DOS emulation?  If it does, then it is a problem.  What does
>Linux do if the hardware settings of the memory map overlap?  There isn't
>anything any operating system can do to fix this problem on the PC.  It
>isn't possible in its' *hardware*, period...

Linux doesn't emulate DOS, Linux emulates Unix :-)

There is a DOS emulator for Linux, DOSEMU, currently in alpha tests,
which runs quite a lot of DOS software, including Windows 3.0.
>
>>TSRs aren't a problem in Unix.
>
>They are if you have DOS emulation... :-(

I could run all the TSR's I used to use under MSDOS with DOSEMU. Even in
the emulated high memory area, not only in the emulated conventional
memory.
>
>The PC problem is random.  You are just lucky.  A large percentage of
>PC users using advanced types of operating systems *will* have a problem.
>Some PCs are set up different than others (jumpers, boeards, etc), causing
>PC high memory crash problem.  This is why one PC will work just fine
>with an operating system, while a different one configured with similar
>hardware will choke...

Could you post some specific examples of unlucky PC owners, who couldn't
install and use Linux on their 386+ boxes because of the problems you're
referring to?

I've installed Linux on two notebooks and it worked, even with the power
saving features of those notebooks enabled (I was expecting troubles in
this area, but everything worked fine).

