::: "TB" == Tony Burzio <aetc@nic.cerf.net> writes:

 TB> In article <1994Sep17.183718.2857@belvedere.sbay.org> root@belvedere.sbay.org (David E. Fox) writes:
 >> : Ask your vendor of PC UNIXen, how do you exclude the sections of high memory
 >> : (640K -> 1MB) that are redirected to interface cards?  If the answer is
 >> : "Huh?", choose another brand... :-)  If they get testy, ask them to explain
 >> Linux loads at the 1 megabyte boundary and remaps the 0-640K area, from
 >> what I know. This isn't a problem.

 TB> Does Linux do DOS emulation?  If it does, then it is a problem.  What does

It's not.  Any well-designed DOS emulator not just emulates DOS, but it also
emulates PC-hardware.

 TB> Linux do if the hardware settings of the memory map overlap?  There isn't

Again, the trick is that all hardware is emulated (though it is possible to
provide physical access to certain devices like UARTs at your own risk).

For example, every emulator process emulates an entire i8250 UART chip to the
DOS environment, completely with its registers etc., while translating all
actions to /dev/tty? on the unix side.

 TB> anything any operating system can do to fix this problem on the PC.  It
 TB> isn't possible in its' *hardware*, period...

Not at all.  Actually, Insignia's SoftPC works in a similar way: emulate the
entire hardware;  10 spc processes make its DOS `see' a WD1003 type MFM
harddisk, where there is none.

There's simply no other way to completely emulate a DOS PC.

The whole point is that the flakyness of DOS-PC's comes for 99% from DOS, and
for just 98% (sic!) from its hardware.  :-)

-Raymond
