Tony Burzio (aetc@nic.cerf.net) wrote:

: They are if you have DOS emulation... :-(

If you need Unix, run Unix.  If you need DOS, run DOS.  If you need
BOTH it's time to port your app.

Granted, it is nice to emulate DOS apps under Unix, but my longtime
experience with both DOS and Windows as well as Unix indicates that
it's more headache than it's worth.  Given the cost of my time, I
often find it cheaper to simply purcahse dedicated hardware for each
OS. (or program loader, in the DOS case.)

: The PC problem is random.  You are just lucky.  A large percentage of
: PC users using advanced types of operating systems *will* have a problem.

While I am no fan of the PC non-architecture, and I'm sure you are
right about the hardware device mapping probs, I find that both Linux
and FreeBSD run like champs on the PC almost all the time.  Especially
if you don't have a Taiwanese cheapo motherboard.

For a test, anon ftp to ftp.cdrom.com.  It's running FreeBSD with
64Meg (soon to be 128 Meg, I think) and it does an excellent job of
things.

: Some PCs are set up different than others (jumpers, boeards, etc), causing
: PC high memory crash problem.  This is why one PC will work just fine
: with an operating system, while a different one configured with similar
: hardware will choke...

If one inteneds to use a PC for any reason, one must be familiar with
jumper settings, DMA access, IRQs and all the rest.  One must know
what one is doing.  (I'm *not* saying you don't know what you are
doing!)  I totally agree that workstations are cleaner and much more
stable platforms for Unix.  But I disagree that the PC mess is more
often a failure than not for a trained engineer.

